---
import { codeToHtml } from 'shiki';
import CommandList from '../../../../../components/CommandList.astro';
import LessonGrid from '../../../../../components/LessonGrid.astro';
import LessonPage from '../../../../../components/LessonPage.astro';
import LessonSection from '../../../../../components/LessonSection.astro';
import TagList from '../../../../../components/TagList.astro';

const commands = [
  'dotnet --info',
  'mkdir dotnet-api-lab && cd dotnet-api-lab',
  'dotnet new web -n HelloApi',
  'cd HelloApi',
  'dotnet run',
  'curl http://localhost:5000',
];

const statusEndpoint = `app.MapGet("/status", () => new
{
    Service = "HelloApi",
    Status = "ok",
    CheckedAt = DateTimeOffset.UtcNow
});`;

const tinyApi = `var app = WebApplication.Create(args);

app.MapGet("/", () => "Hello World!");

app.Run();`;

const freshProgram = `var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);
var app = builder.Build();

app.MapGet("/", () => "Hello World!");

app.Run();`;

const runStatus = `dotnet run
curl http://localhost:5000/status`;

const [tinyApiHtml, freshProgramHtml, statusEndpointHtml, runStatusHtml] = await Promise.all([
  codeToHtml(tinyApi, { lang: 'csharp', theme: 'github-dark' }),
  codeToHtml(freshProgram, { lang: 'csharp', theme: 'github-dark' }),
  codeToHtml(statusEndpoint, { lang: 'csharp', theme: 'github-dark' }),
  codeToHtml(runStatus, { lang: 'shellscript', theme: 'github-dark' }),
]);
---

<LessonPage
  title="Lesson 1 · Your first .NET API"
  heading="Your first minimal API"
  lede="Today’s win: understand the smallest useful ASP.NET Core API and run it from the terminal on Linux or macOS. No Visual Studio, no Windows-only assumptions."
  backHref="/topics/dotnet/"
  backLabel=".NET lessons"
>
  <LessonSection title="The mental model">
    <p>
      A .NET API is just a program that starts a web server, maps HTTP routes to C# functions, and waits for requests.
      ASP.NET Core’s <strong>Minimal APIs</strong> let you express that directly in <code>Program.cs</code>.
    </p>
    <LessonGrid>
      <div>
        <h3>Think in three steps</h3>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Build an app</strong>: create the web application object.</li>
          <li><strong>Map endpoints</strong>: say which URL and HTTP method call which function.</li>
          <li><strong>Run the app</strong>: start listening for HTTP requests.</li>
        </ol>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3>The tiny version</h3>
        <Fragment set:html={tinyApiHtml} />
      </div>
    </LessonGrid>
  </LessonSection>

  <LessonSection title="Your terminal path">
    <p>
      On Linux and macOS, the official path is the <code>dotnet</code> CLI. The CLI comes with the .NET SDK and works the same way across both systems.
    </p>
    <CommandList commands={commands} />
    <p><small>
      If <code>dotnet --info</code> fails, install the .NET SDK first. Prefer the official Microsoft package instructions for your Linux distro or macOS installer/Homebrew route.
    </small></p>
  </LessonSection>

  <LessonSection title="Open <code>Program.cs</code>">
    <p>For a fresh <code>dotnet new web</code> app, expect something close to this:</p>
    <Fragment set:html={freshProgramHtml} />
    <p>
      Read it literally: create a builder, build an app, map <code>GET /</code> to a function, run the web server.
      The lambda <code>() =&gt; "Hello World!"</code> is the request handler.
    </p>
  </LessonSection>

  <LessonSection title="Make it an API, not just hello world">
    <p>Replace the route with a small JSON response:</p>
    <Fragment set:html={statusEndpointHtml} />
    <p>Then run again and call it:</p>
    <Fragment set:html={runStatusHtml} />
    <p>
      If the console says it is listening on a different port, use that port. On modern templates it may choose a random dev port like <code>http://localhost:5123</code>.
    </p>
  </LessonSection>

  <LessonSection title="Linux/macOS caveats" variant="warning">
    <TagList tags={['VS Code is enough', 'Rider is optional', 'Visual Studio is not required']} />
    <p>
      Microsoft docs often mention Visual Studio because many .NET developers use it. For backend APIs, you can stay productive with the SDK, terminal, VS Code or Rider, and normal Unix tools like <code>curl</code>.
    </p>
    <p>
      The important distinction: install the <strong>SDK</strong>, not only the runtime. The runtime runs apps; the SDK creates, builds, and tests them.
    </p>
  </LessonSection>

  <LessonSection title="Retrieval checkpoint — reply in Discord" variant="checkpoint">
    <p>Before the next lesson, answer these from memory:</p>
    <ol>
      <li>In your own words, what does <code>app.MapGet("/status", ...)</code> do?</li>
      <li>What is the difference between the .NET SDK and the .NET runtime?</li>
      <li>Paste the JSON you get from your <code>/status</code> endpoint, or paste the error if it fails.</li>
    </ol>
  </LessonSection>

  <LessonSection title="Primary source">
    <p>
      Read Microsoft Learn’s Minimal APIs overview and .NET CLI overview when you want the official reference:
      <a href="https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/aspnet/core/fundamentals/minimal-apis/overview">Minimal APIs</a>
      and <a href="https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/tools/">.NET CLI</a>.
    </p>
  </LessonSection>
</LessonPage>
